Session 06 Artificial Neural Networks¶

CCMVI2085U Machine Learning for Predictive Analytics in Business @ CBS ISUP 2020

Course coordinator: Bowei Chen | Email: bc.acc@cbs.dk

Artificial neural networks (in short neural networks or ANNs) have a range of real-world applications in the business domain, ranging from customer credit scoring, to bankruptcy prediction, stock and commodity selection and trading, sales forecasting, new product design and target marketing. This session aims to give you a brief introduction to ANNs and the implementation of a simple ANN model in Python for solving classification and regression problems.

Motivating example¶

Suppose we are business analysts working with a client – a large seaside resort company whose business is to provide affordable holiday family fun activities and entertainments. The company would like us to develop a model which can recommend this summer’s events to the booked customers (i.e., booked flats). Our goal is to develop a data-driven model which can segment customers from the last summer’s data and use it to recommend events to this summer’s new bookings.

As the response variable contains three different values of summer’s events (i.e., spa, shows, and outdoor activities), this is a multi-class classification problem. There are a number of classification algorithms can be used here. In this session, we are going to develop a simple ANN to segment consumers.

Data preparation¶

Once we have loaded the data and have performed the initial check with it. Another important stage is to preprocess data for the our target machine learning algorithms, including data encoding, scaling or standardization, and spliting. Here we can simply call this stage data preparation or data preprocessing

Data encoding¶

The term encoding means we convert the data values into a specified format or form. Decoding is the reverse process of encoding which is to extract the information from the converted format. In the data preparation stage, data encoding is mainly for feature encoding and/or label encoding. Sometimes, we just simply say feature encoding for both.

We can use pandas.get_dummies to encode categorical feature variables. Here we exclude the response variable because it has three categories.

df_features = pd.get_dummies(df.iloc[:, :-1], drop_first=True)

Scaling and standardization¶

Machine learning algorithms can work better when features are on a relatively similar scale and close to normally distributed. Scaling and standardization are popular methods to perform transformation on numerical feature variables.

Let $x$ denote the (univariate) variable and its values over the dataset can be indexed by $n = 1, 2, \ldots, N$. Then

  • Min-max is a popular scaling method, which means the change in the range of the variable values but not in the shape of the distribution. The range is often set between 0 and 1. $$ \widetilde{x}_{n} = \frac{x_n - \text{min}(x)}{\text{max}(x) - \text{min}(x)}. $$ If scaling to a range between $a$ and $b$, then the min-max can be calculated by $$ \widetilde{x}_{n} = a + \frac{(x_n - \text{min}(x))(b-a)}{\text{max}(x)-\text{min}(x)} $$

  • Standardization (or z-score nomarlization) means changing the values so that the output distribution is close to a normal distribution. It should noted that it can behave badly if the individual features do not more or less look like normally distributed data. When we perform standardization, scaling is often implied. $$ \widetilde{x}_{n} = \frac{x_n - \bar{x}}{\text{std}(x)} = \frac{x_n - \bar{x}}{\sqrt{\text{var}(x)}}, $$ where $\text{var}(x)$ is the variance of the sample data.

We can use MinMaxScaler and StandardScaler to perform min-max and standardization for numerical variables.

from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

price = x[:, 1].reshape(-1, 1)

min_max = MinMaxScaler()
min_max.fit(price)
price_minmax = min_max.transform(price)

standard_scaler = StandardScaler()
standard_scaler.fit(price)
price_standard_scaler = standard_scaler.transform(price)

For this consumer segmentation project, let's apply standardization (z-score normalization) to numerical feature variables.

min_max = StandardScaler()
min_max.fit(x[:, :5])
x[:, :5] = min_max.transform(x[:, :5])

Artificial neural networks¶

What is an artificial neural network?¶

ANNs are a special tribe of machine learning in which algorithms process signals via interconnected nodes called neurons. They mimic the architecture of biological nervous systems so ANN's untimate goal is to model the brain.

Types of neural network¶

Fig source: https://www.xenonstack.com/blog/artificial-neural-network-applications

Multi-layer perceptron¶

As usual, we denote the dataset by notation $\mathcal{D}$, where

$$\mathcal{D} = \{(\boldsymbol{x}_1, y_1), \cdots, (\boldsymbol{x}_N, y_N)\} = \{(\boldsymbol{x}_n, y_n)\}_{n=1}^{N}$$$$ \boldsymbol{X} = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} x_{11} & \cdots & x_{1D} \\ \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ x_{N1} & \cdots & x_{ND} \\ \end{array} \right] = \left[ \begin{array}{c} \boldsymbol{x}_1^\top \\ \vdots\\ \boldsymbol{x}_N^\top \\ \end{array} \right] , \ \ \ \ \ \boldsymbol{y} = \left[ \begin{array}{ccc} y_{1} \\ \vdots \\ y_{N} \\ \end{array} \right]$$

Here we know the response variable $y$ has $K$ classes.

How does the MLP work?¶

The following the a simple architecture or structure of a multi-layer perceptron (MLP). It contains three layers, input layer, hidden layer and output layer. In some references, we also call this two-layer neural network (not including the input layer in the counting).

From the input layer to the hidden layer

From the hidden layer to the output layer

Mathematical representation of the neural network¶

  • With bias term
$$ o_k = \gamma^{(2)} \left(\sum_{q=1}^{Q} w_{kq}^{(2)}\gamma^{(1)}\left( \sum_{d=1}^{D} w_{qd}^{(1)}x_d + w_{q0}^{(1)}\right) + w_{k0}^{(2)}\right) $$
  • Absorbinng bias term
$$ o_k = \gamma^{(2)} \left(\sum_{q=0}^{Q} w_{kq}^{(2)}\gamma^{(1)}\left( \sum_{d=0}^{D} w_{qd}^{(1)}x_d \right) \right) $$
  • Matrix form
$$ \boldsymbol{o} = \gamma^{(2)}(\boldsymbol{W}^{(2) \top} \left[ \gamma^{(1)} \left(\boldsymbol{W}^{(1) \top} \boldsymbol{x}\right)\right]) $$

Popular activation functions¶

  • Sigmoid $$\gamma(u) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-u}}$$
  • Tanh $$\gamma(u) = \frac{e^{u} - e^{-u}}{e^{u} + e^{-u}}$$
  • Rectified linear unit (ReLU) $$\gamma(u) = \max\{0, u\}$$

Cross-entropy loss function for multi-class classification¶

The cross-entropy loss function measures the performance of a classification model whose output is a probability value between 0 and 1. For an observation, it is defined as

$$- \sum_{k=1}^K y_k log\{p_k\}$$

where $y_k \in \{0,1\}$ and $p_k$ shows the predicted probability of an observation is of class $k$, $k=1,\ldots, K$.

For $N$ observations, we have

$$ \mathscr{L}(\boldsymbol{W}^{(1)}, \boldsymbol{W}^{(2)}) = - \sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{k=1}^{K} y_k^{(n)} \log\{p_k^{(n)}\} = - \sum_{n=1}^{N} \sum_{k=1}^{K} y_k^{(n)} \log\left\{ \frac{e^{o_k^{(n)}}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} e^{o_k^{(n)}}}\right\}. $$

Backpropagation¶

To solve the above optimization problem, we can use the gradient descent method, which we saw in the previous sessions. However, since a neural network contains a large number of weights, directly calculating partial derivatives of weights from the input layers to the output layers is time consuming. We can use the backpropagation algorithm (BP) together with gradient decent to estimate the weights. I am not going to further discuss this here. Further references about the standard BP can be found in Bishop Chapter 5.3

Implementing MLP using sklearn in Python¶

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.neural_network.MLPClassifier.html?highlight=mlp#sklearn.neural_network.MLPClassifier

from sklearn.neural_network import MLPClassifier

mlp_clf = MLPClassifier(random_state=100, max_iter=10000)
mlp_clf.fit(x_train, y_train)

MLPClassifier(activation='relu', alpha=0.0001, batch_size='auto', beta_1=0.9,
              beta_2=0.999, early_stopping=False, epsilon=1e-08,

              power_t=0.5, random_state=100, shuffle=True, solver='adam',
              tol=0.0001, validation_fraction=0.1, verbose=False,
              warm_start=False)
y_predproba_train = mlp_clf.predict_proba(x_train)
y_predlabel_train = mlp_clf.predict(x_train)
